  <!-- Article Content -->
  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
      <p>In the summer of 2022, a landmark paper in <em>Molecular Psychiatry</em> systematically dismantled the serotonin theory of depression — the idea that low serotonin causes depression, and that SSRIs work by correcting this chemical imbalance. The evidence simply didn't support it, and the review said so unambiguously.</p>

      <p>What the 2022 review didn't do — what no single paper can do — is replace a wrong theory with a right one. Demolishing the dominant model left psychiatry with a pharmacologically useful class of drugs, an uncertain mechanism, and no agreed-upon alternative framework for what depression actually is.</p>

      <p>A study published in March 2026 offers what may be the most structurally coherent alternative yet. The research team, examining brain and blood cells from young adults with major depressive disorder, found a specific and unexpected anomaly in cellular energy metabolism — one that fits a range of clinical observations that the serotonin model never adequately explained.</p>

      <p>The depression is not a chemistry problem. It may be an energy problem.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="what-they-found" class="reveal">
      <h2>What They Found</h2>

      <p>The study recruited young adults with current major depressive disorder and matched healthy controls and subjected their cells — both brain-derived and peripheral blood cells — to metabolic analysis measuring ATP (adenosine triphosphate, the cell's primary energy currency) production at rest and under demand.</p>

      <p>The finding was counterintuitive. Cells from depressed participants produced <em>more</em> ATP at rest than cells from healthy controls — a state of baseline energy overproduction that the researchers interpreted as the cells running a kind of metabolic overdrive without a corresponding functional output.</p>

      <p>But when demand was placed on the cells — when they were stimulated to ramp up energy production for active tasks — the depressed cells failed to respond appropriately. They couldn't increase output relative to their already-elevated baseline. They were idling at high RPM but couldn't accelerate.</p>

      <p>The researchers described this as a "mitochondrial ceiling" effect: the mitochondria were already operating near maximum capacity at rest, leaving no headroom for the surges in energy production that active brain function requires. The cells were simultaneously exhausted and hyperactive.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"The mitochondria were already operating near maximum capacity at rest, leaving no headroom for the surges in energy production that active brain function requires."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="why-this-matters" class="reveal">
      <h2>Why This Matters</h2>

      <p>The mitochondrial model doesn't replace the entire serotonin hypothesis — that would be premature and epistemically overconfident. But it explains several clinical features of depression that the serotonin model never handled well.</p>

      <p><strong>The fatigue paradox.</strong> The most common complaint in depression is not sadness. It is fatigue, cognitive slowing, and a sense of effort attached to tasks that should be effortless. This is not what you'd expect from a simple deficiency in a mood-regulating neurotransmitter. It is exactly what you'd expect from neurons that cannot meet their energy demands during active processing.</p>

      <p><strong>The cognitive symptoms.</strong> Depression impairs working memory, attention, and processing speed in ways that are often more functionally disabling than the mood symptoms. These are precisely the functions that place the highest moment-to-moment demand on neuronal energy production.</p>

      <p><strong>The anhedonia.</strong> Loss of pleasure — the inability to feel reward from activities that were previously rewarding — has always been the most difficult depressive symptom to explain through serotonin. Reward processing in the brain is metabolically expensive, heavily dependent on dopamine in circuits that require robust ATP production to function. A mitochondrial ceiling explains hedonic blunting more naturally than serotonergic deficit does.</p>

      <p><strong>The morning worsening.</strong> Many people with depression experience their worst symptoms in the morning, improving somewhat as the day progresses. This pattern is consistent with the idea that a system operating near metabolic capacity has the most difficulty when waking demands peak rapidly from a baseline that was already compromised during sleep.</p>

      <p><strong>The exercise treatment effect.</strong> Exercise is one of the most reliably effective treatments for depression across the evidence base — more effective than antidepressants for mild-to-moderate cases in several comparative studies. The conventional explanation has always been somewhat vague: endorphins, serotonin, BDNF, "mood-boosting effects." The mitochondrial model offers a more specific mechanism: exercise is the most potent known stimulus for mitochondrial biogenesis — the production of new, functional mitochondria. It doesn't just temporarily boost mood; it rebuilds the energy infrastructure.</p>
    </section>

